  "description": "Wilhelm Arthur Yngve Hagwall was a Swedish Commander Captain in the Royal Swedish Navy. He was born on September 20th, 1904, in Västervik to Captain of Västgöta Regiment Hans Arthur H. and Märtha Allvin. He married Inga Borgstedt in 1929 and had three children: Gunvor, Claes, and Maj. Hagwall passed his studentexamen in Skövde in 1922 and attended the Royal Swedish Naval Staff College's general course from 1931-1932 and the torpedo course from 1933-1934. He enlisted in the navy as a midshipman in 1925, became a sub-lieutenant in 1927, a lieutenant in 1928, captain in 1938, and Commander Captain of the second group in 1944. Hagwall taught for several years in torpedo training at the Royal Naval Academy in Karlskrona and served as commanding officer on several submarines and as divisional commander from 1940-1942 and chief of torpedo and mine depots in Karlskrona since 1944. He accompanied a naval expedition to distant waters in 1922-1923. Hagwall was awarded the Order of the Sword, Officer 1st Class, and the Navy Medal for Shooting with Torpedoes."
